<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1059,211,321]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirsch" authorityYear="1871" box="[468,594,211,232]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="966" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,594,211,232]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Aphelocerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
KIRSCH was revised in 2005 (OPITZ 2005). This work included a key to species. 
<taxonomicName box="[535,717,241,262]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yoro">
<emphasis box="[535,717,241,262]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Aphelocerus yoro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key out to 
<emphasis box="[948,1058,241,262]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">A. capillus</emphasis>
OPITZ from which 
<taxonomicName box="[351,428,270,292]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yoro">
<emphasis box="[351,428,270,292]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">A. yoro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing broader phallobasic lobes and angular incurvature of the lobe apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1059,336,623]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,336,358]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" unit="mm" value="5.2">5.2 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,337,358]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="967" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,337,359]" captionStart="Figs 270-273" captionStartId="95.[151,191,1512,1534]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,224,1495]" captionTargetId="figure@95.[153,1061,196,1495]" captionTargetPageId="95" captionText="Figs 270-273: Habitus; (270) Aphelocerus yoro; (271) Perilypus alpinus; (272) P. apunctus; (273) P. arsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746796" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746796/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 270</figureCitation>
. Color: Black; row of white setae at base of elytral sutural margin contiguous with anterior patch of white setae, elytral disc posterior patch of white setae well developed. Head: Interocular depression and frontal umbo shallow; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[785,852,425,447]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres filiform, progressively shorter and wider towards capitulum, capitulum compact; eyes finely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 15/40). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[268,357,513,535]" captionStart="Figs 101-117" captionStartId="75.[151,191,1477,1499]" captionTargetBox="[152,1030,198,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@75.[152,1030,198,1465]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 101-117: Pronota; (101) Aphelocerus ligulus; (102) A. yoro; (103) Ridica achira; (104) R. merida; (105) Ampleris cacuminis; (106) Plocamocera catalexis; (107) Aphelocerus tigra; (108) A. sparicapillus; (109) A. nolus; (110) A. magnipannus; (111) Pyticeroides desodes; (112) Cregya petalosa; (113) C. livida; (114) C. tobagoensis; (115) C. maura; (116) Pujoliclerus flavidus; (117) Amboakis collucoatis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746756" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746756/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 102</figureCitation>
) slightly oblong, very finely punctate; (PW/PL 75/80); elytral disc with two patches of white setae, anterior patch obliquely positioned and oblong, posterior patch subquadrate, disc impressed with small setiferous punctures (EL/EW 225/65). Abdomen: Pygidium transverse 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[564,571,600,622]" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">/</emphasis>
scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[834,925,601,623]" captionStart="Figs 207-212" captionStartId="84.[151,191,1256,1278]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetId="figure@84.[153,1061,199,1242]" captionTargetPageId="84" captionText="Figs 207-212: Aedeagi; (207) Aphelocerus tigra; (208) A. yoro; (209) Perilypus alpinus; (210) P. apunctus; (211) P. arsus; (212) P. izabal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746774" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746774/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="967">Fig. 208.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
